The subprocess module in Python is used to spawn new processes, connect to their input/output/error pipes, and obtain their return codes.
It provides a way to interact with the operating system and execute external commands or scripts from within a Python script.

Real life examples -

Running System Commands:
subprocess.run(['gzip', 'myfile.txt'])

Git Operations:
subprocess.run(['git', 'clone', 'https://github.com/example/repo.git'])

Database Operations:
subprocess.run(['mysqldump', '-u', 'username', '-p', 'password', 'database_name'])

System Information Retrieval:
subprocess.run(['df', '-h'])

Running External Scripts:
subprocess.run(['bash', 'script.sh'])

